'''Pomozhenie Rodam Icon of the Mother of God''' (Икона Божией Матери «Поможение родам») — a revered {{ill|icon|ru|икона|12=draft}} of the {{ill|Mother of God|ru|Богородица|12=draft}}, honored in the {{ill|Orthodox Church|ru|Православная церковь|12=draft}} for aiding women in childbirth. The icon is also known as ''Pomoshchnitsa v Rodakh'' ('Helper in Childbirth') or ''Pomogatelnitsa Zhenam Chady Rozhdati'' ('Helper to Women Bearing Children'). Its feast day is {{СС|8|January|||26|December}}.

== Iconography ==
The icon’s origin is unknown, but two traditional depictions exist:
* The Mother of God is shown full-length with her hands raised in prayer, and the Christ Child appears on her chest, similar to the {{ill|Sign Icon of the Theotokos|ru|Знамение Божией Матери|12=draft}}.
* The Mother of God is depicted with uncovered hair and crossed hands on her chest, with the Christ Child below, blessing with an {{ill|Old Believer sign|ru|Именословное перстосложение|12=draft}}. The entire image is placed on a crescent moon<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://azbyka.ru/days/ikona-pomoshchnica-v-rodah|title=Icon of the Mother of God 'Helper in Childbirth'|access-date=2022-04-18|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220418185415/https://azbyka.ru/days/ikona-pomoshchnica-v-rodah|archive-date=2022-04-18}}</ref>.

The icon’s veneration was especially strong before the revolution, with the feast on December 26 (Old Style) coinciding with the traditional midwives' festival known as {{ill|Babyi Kashi|ru|Бабьи каши|12=draft}}, celebrated in southern and western Russia and Siberia<ref>{{СДЭС|Бабин день|автор={{ill|Zelenina, Elvira Ivanovna|ru|Зеленина, Эльвира Ивановна|12=draft}}, {{ill|Sedakova, Irina Alexandrovna|ru|Седакова, Ирина Александровна|12=draft}}|том=1|страницы=123–125}}</ref>.
